(1+x)/(1-x)>e^{2x}
0<x<1
1>\sum x^k(\frac{2^k}{k!}-1)
\frac{2^k}{k!}>1
0<x<1
0<x<1
0<x<1
\begin{align*}\frac{1+x}{1-x}&=(1+x)\frac{1}{1-x}=(1+x)(1+x+x^2+x^3+\ldots)=\\\\&=(1+x+x^2+x^3+\ldots)+(x+x^2+x^3+x^4\ldots)=1+2(x+x^2+x^3+\ldots)\end{align*}
e^{2x}=\left(1+\frac{2x}{1!}+\frac{(2x)^2}{2!}+\frac{(2x)^3}{3!}\dots \right)=\left(1+\frac{2}{1!}x+\frac{2^2}{2!}x^2+\frac{2^3}{3!}x^3\dots \right)
\begin{align*}\frac{1+x}{1-x}-e^{2x}&=1+2(x+x^2+x^3+\ldots)-\left(1+\frac{2x}{1!}+\frac{(2x)^2}{2!}+\frac{(2x)^3}{3!}\dots \right)=\\\\&=\underbrace{(2-1)}_{>0}x^2+\underbrace{\left(2-\frac{2^3}{3!}\right)}_{>0}x^3+\underbrace{\left(2-\frac{2^4}{4!}\right)}_{>0}x^4+\ldots>0\end{align*}
\frac{1+x}{1-x}-e^{2x}>0 \implies \frac{1+x}{1-x}>e^{2x}
2^n<n!
n\ge 4
n>4
n-4
